A New Study on Fourth Downs: Go for It

By Brian Burke
September 17, 2009 7:00 am September 17, 2009 7:00 am

(Brian Burke, a former Navy pilot who has taken up the less dangerous hobby of N.F.L. statistical analysis, runs Advanced NFL Stats, a blog about football, math and human behavior.)

Here’s a thought exercise for you. Imagine that for decades no one ever thought of the punt. Teams knew nothing else than to run or pass on 4th down. And then one day it’s invented. Some guy comes up to a coach and says, “Kick the ball on every 4th down and the other team gets possession 37 yards further down the field.” The coach would think he was crazy: “Wait, you want me to give up one quarter of my opportunities for a first down on every series…just for 35 yards of field position? Do you realize how much that’s going to kill our chances of scoring?”

And that coach would be absolutely right. It’s funny how boxed in our thinking can be. Except for the most desperate of circumstances or with inches to go just outside of field-goal range, today’s N.F.L. coaches will choose to punt.

Every single serious study of 4th-down decisions has found that, in most situations, teams would be better off by going for the conversion attempt rather than kicking. I’ve recently completed a study of 4th-down decisions that confirms what some fans already know, that it pays to be more aggressive. Those short on time might want to skip ahead to the bottom line.

In normal football situations, when neither team is ahead by much, and when the clock is not yet a factor, we can weigh the costs and benefits of each possible decision. Field-goal attempts, punts and conversion attempts can be valued by using a concept called Expected Points. A 1st down at any given yard line has an equivalent point value based on the average of the next score in the game. For example, a 1st down at midfield is worth 1.9 expected points.

Since we know the average punt distances and field-goal percentages from various field positions, we can accurately estimate the expected point values of kicks. And since we know the conversion percentages on 4th-down attempts, we can value those, too. When the values are compared, it becomes clear that going for the first down is the better decision far more often than most people, and most coaches, think.

You might ask: If it’s so obvious, then why don’t coaches go for it more often? There are a number of good explanations. The authors of the football research classic “The Hidden Game of Football” note that in the early days of the sport, it was rare for a team to score more than once all game. A punt basically guaranteed the opponent wouldn’t score on the next drive. Professor David Romer, author of one of the definitive papers on the subject, theorized that coaches are worried more about job security than winning. If a coach goes for it and fails, it’s his fault. But if he punts and loses, well, that’s just football, and his players take the blame.

I buy those explanations, but I also think it has something to do with what economists call Prospect Theory. In short, almost all people tend to fear losses far more than they value equivalent gains. In this perspective, a punt is considered the “break-even” decision. A failed conversion attempt is seen as a loss, and a successful attempt is seen as a gain. But the loss is feared disproportionately, and the result is clouded decision-making.

Above, I wrote “in normal football situations.” When time becomes a factor, or when a team falls far behind, we need a different way to analyze decisions. For these situations we need to rely on a Win Probability model, an index of how likely a team is to win based on all relevant game variables.

There’s an arbitrage opportunity in the N.F.L. right now. The first coach who takes advantage of a more aggressive 4th-down doctrine could win a whole lot of games, and N.F.L. strategy could get a whole lot more interesting.

AY September 17, 2009 · 9:23 am

Your paragraph on prospect theory is interesting.

There was a similar study regarding putting on the PGA tour by researchers from Wharton School of Business earlier this year. Using shot-tracking software, they found that no matter the length of the putt, PGA pros tended to be more aggressive on their par putts than their birdie putts (about 3% more accurate). The conventional thinking was that not making a birdie was disapppointing, but not as unfortunate as missing a par putt and making a bogey.

Judge Smails September 17, 2009 · 9:52 am

All he’s doing is studying expected values. Its easier to apply cousin is the analysis regarding the two point conversion. Some studies have show that teams are successful slightly more than 50% of the time (upwards of 55%). Therefore, the expected value is slightly more than 1 – convenient since 1 is the expected value of 100% accuracy on kicking extra points. Yet despite the odds and expected values, coaches keep kicking.

Another exampe of conservative behavior is the show “Deal or No Deal” where contestants often, if not always, take the sure thing deal when the expected value based on the remaining possibilities is higher.

jvill September 17, 2009 · 10:25 am

What’s amazing about this analysis is:

a) these ideas have been around for a while

b) they are generally just the application of pretty standard business evaluation and statistical techniques (e.g. “expected value” and “prospect theory”)

c) the comments on this thread about 4th and longs and the other team getting the ball (two factors which would be included in the expected value analysis) indeed illustrates the biggest barrier to coaches using these methods — fans don’t understand it, which means the media won’t understand it, which means coaches will be fired for doing things that are probabilistically smart and would win games for their teams. After all, some of the sentences you wrote require some patience to understand, and we can’t have that!

Calling it an arbitrage is perfect. We’ll see if any coach has the courage to do what’s right in the face of screaming fans complaining about things they don’t understand.

Michelle September 17, 2009 · 10:36 am

The analysis fails to take into consideration the psychology of the game. There is more at stake than “fear of failure”. Because most coaches punt on 4th down, the defense “knows” it only has to defend successfully for 3 downs. When a coach decides to go for it on 4th down, the defense suffers a very small letdown that plays to the advantage of the offense. If going for it on 4th became the norm, successful 4th down conversions would decrease over time.

As FDR said, “The only thing we have to fear is fear itself”. A coach’s first motto should be, “No fear”. No fear for job security, No fear for the consequences of aggressive play calling. The best example is the Patriots-Bills game. The Bills would have won if they hadn’t gone conservative with their defense in the second half.

Recifense September 17, 2009 · 10:50 am

One coach in the NFL already has a more aggressive fourth down approach than the others: Bill Belechick. And it’s paid off for the Patriots.

John Scheef September 17, 2009 · 10:55 am

The flip side of this analysis is whether punt return teams should focus more on the punt block rather than the punt return. It seems that most punt return teams make little or no effort to try to block the punt and instead seem to only make sure that there isn’t a fake punt. It seems that a similar cost-benefit analysis could be done for aggressively trying to block punts, especially since very few punt returns make significant yardage. It seems that the possibility of blocking the punt or hurrying the punter into a poor punt would, in most instances, outweigh the risk of a running into the kicker penalty or fair catch. Also, the punt block pressure may, in fact, cause the punt protection team to less aggressively cover the punt.

Likewise there is a higher tendency to punt when there are disadvantageous team-opponent dynamics on 4th down.

This skews the data toward more favorable 4th down outcomes.

Neil Cohen September 17, 2009 · 11:25 am

I think that a complete analysis should also include where the offensive team gets the ball back next (a complete cycle of possession). If you punt instead of going for it on your end of the field, then you may get the ball back in a better position the next time (if your expected yards gained by going for it is less than a punt). For example, if you punt and hold the opponents, then you get the ball back where you punted from (if their punt is the same length as yours). if, instead, you turn the ball over on downs and hold them and they punt, you get the ball 30 yards further back.

Len September 17, 2009 · 3:25 pm

This report is simplistic. It’s obviously reporting averages of a distribution of outcomes. There is a different expected value of punting vs. going for it depending on how many yards you have to go. And there is a different expected value depending on the yard line. I’m willing to bet that if it’s 4th down and 15 yards to go from your own 5 yard line, punting is going to have a better expected value than going for it. It would be interesting to see a table of probabilities plotting yards to go against yard line. How about it?

Jim Rossi September 17, 2009 · 3:46 pm

I buy the author’s conclusion: an arbitrage opportunity for more aggressive 4th down play-calling.

However I think the focus on statistics incompletely measures the consequences of punting or not punting (incomprehensibly, as some posts mention). Also as other posts mentioned, if going for it on 4th down became the norm, the entire dynamics of the game would change – defensive play-calling, personnel substitutions, etc. and these stats would not be terribly enlightening. And the effect of going-for-it on field position is not adequately factored in – and indeed that’s the entire point of punting.

A saying from science is apropos: We should use statistics like a drunk man uses a lightpost – for support, not illumination.

kyle c September 17, 2009 · 3:51 pm

Fourth down conversions are so successful, because they’re only attempted in situations of short yardage. Coaches don’t go for it on fourth-and-10, and if they did, the fourth down success ratio would revert closer to the third-down conversion ratio. However, going for it on fourth-down can be a major confidence booster for the offense. The coach is showing a great deal of confidence in his offense to offer them the make-or-break option. That bump may help, but it could also be detrimental by making it more difficult for players to focus on execution.

JJ September 17, 2009 · 4:23 pm

I agree with some of the others regarding the success rate of 4th down conversions being oversimplified. I would guess that a great majority of these instances are from 2-3 yards or shorter. If this is the case, the probability of converting 4th downs is artificially inflated.

sean f September 17, 2009 · 4:38 pm

The study factors in the distance required to make it. Even if you assume third down conversion rates for fourth down it still makes far more sense to go for it far more often than coaches do.

Also if teams adjusted their schemes and play calling then the relative advantage of going for it on fourth might change, but given the current tactics in use, points are leaving points on the field by not going for it more.

Next time you watch a game, ask yourself on each fourth down when your team is on defense. Am I relieved the offense is punting or do I wish they would go for it so my team’s defense could stuff them? I suspect that anything near midfield and under five to seven yards you are relieved that they are punting.
